<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1920-06-24T10:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1920-06-24T10:00:00-05:00" n="451" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d451">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">462.00 R 29/249: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Wallace</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1920-06-24T16:00:00+01:00"><hi rend="italic">June 24,
                                            1920—4 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received 6:39
                                    p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                            <p>1321. B–130 for Davis.</p>
                            <p>Reference your 1124, June 16, Uruguayan request for recognition of
                                ownership ex-enemy ships received by Maritime Service. It was
                                decided that this claim would not be taken up in detail until full
                                discussion question of partition of ex-enemy ships. Our
                                representative on Maritime Service arranging confer with Uruguayan
                                representative in London and will note and give friendly
                                consideration to any statements he may make with regard to the case
                                for use when the occasion arises in accordance with your message.
                                Boyden.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Wallace</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>